==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Armadillo
<hw>Ar`ma*dil"lo</hw> <pr>(⟦aum⟧r`m⟦adot⟧*d⟦icr⟧l"l⟦osl⟧)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Armadillos</plw>
<pr>(-l⟦omac⟧z)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Sp. <ets>armadillo</ets>, dim. of
<ets>armado</ets> armed, p. p. of <ets>armar</ets> to arm. So called
from being armed with a bony shell.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>
<sd>(a)</sd> <def>Any edentate animal if the family
<fam>Dasypid⟦ae⟧</fam>, peculiar to America. The body and head are
incased in an armor composed of small bony plates. The armadillos burrow
in the earth, seldom going abroad except at night. When attacked, they
curl up into a ball, presenting the armor on all sides. Their flesh is
good food. There are several species, one of which (the peba) is found
as far north as Texas. See <er>Peba</er>, <er>Poyou</er>,
<er>Tatouay</er>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A genus of small isopod
Crustacea that can roll themselves into a ball.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Armado</ent>⟦br⟧
